EXPERIMENT: D6_NULL_NETWORK_TEST_v1
DATE: 2026-06-06
STATUS: pre-registered
DATASETS: examples/nsclc_egfr_signaling.json, examples/crc_kras_signaling.json,
          examples/pdac_kras_signaling.json, examples/gbm_egfr_signaling.json,
          examples/braf_melanoma_signaling.json, examples/egfr_nsclc_signaling.json

MOTIVATION:
All prior experiments (D3, D4, D5, CANCER_STRUCTURAL_ATLAS_v1) compute delta_r
values and interpret their sign/magnitude as structural damper/anchor positions.
A critical missing validation: are these delta_r values more extreme than what
any randomly connected network of the same size and degree would produce?

If random networks with the same degree sequence produce equally extreme delta_r
values, our structural positions may be artifacts of network size and degree
distribution rather than genuine topological features of cancer signaling.

This null model test is the foundational credibility check for the entire
structural pharmacology framework.

NULL MODEL:
Degree-preserving random rewiring (Maslov-Sneppen algorithm).
For each cancer network and each layer (physical_interaction, coexpression_cancer):
  - Extract the real edge list for that layer
  - Perform 10 × |edges| random edge swaps, each swap preserving node degrees:
      Pick edges (a-b) and (c-d). Swap to (a-d) and (c-b) if:
      (i)  no self-loops (a≠d, c≠b)
      (ii) neither new edge already exists
      (iii) the two new edges are distinct
  - Result: a random graph with identical degree sequence per node per layer,
    but different edge topology

N = 1000 rewirings per cancer network.
Perturbation kernel: same algorithm as CANCER_STRUCTURAL_ATLAS_v1.

PRIMARY HYPOTHESIS (H1, CONFIRMATORY):
For each cancer network, the maximum |delta_r| observed in the real network
exceeds the 95th percentile of maximum |delta_r| values computed across N=1000
degree-preserving random rewirings.

Formally: empirical p-value = fraction of null rewirings where
  max(|delta_r|)_null >= max(|delta_r|)_real  < 0.05

H1 confirmed if at least 5/6 cancer networks individually satisfy p < 0.05.
H1 denied if fewer than 5/6 networks satisfy p < 0.05.

SECONDARY HYPOTHESIS (H2, CONFIRMATORY):
The variance of delta_r across protein nodes is significantly greater in real
cancer networks than in null rewirings.

Formally: empirical p-value = fraction of null rewirings where
  std(delta_r)_null >= std(delta_r)_real  < 0.05

H2 tests whether the SPREAD of structural positions is real (not just the extremes).

TERTIARY HYPOTHESIS (H3, EXPLORATORY):
The sign of the most extreme damper and most extreme anchor is preserved
across >80% of random rewirings in each cancer network.

This tests structural robustness: even in random rewirings, do the same
proteins remain dampers/anchors? If yes, structural positions are intrinsic
to the degree sequence. If no, specific edge topology matters.

DECISION RULE:
H1 confirmed → delta_r extremes are real structural signals, not degree artifacts
H1 denied   → structural positions are degree-sequence artifacts;
               framework requires revision

H2 confirmed → the full damper/anchor distribution is structurally meaningful
H2 denied   → only the extreme values carry signal

H3 result   → informs whether specific topology or degree distribution drives identity

ANALYSIS:
Script: scripts/d6_null_network_test.py
N_rewirings = 1000
n_swaps_per_layer = 10 × |layer_edges|
Layers tested: physical_interaction, coexpression_cancer
Proteins tested: same protein-only set as in CANCER_STRUCTURAL_ATLAS_v1

EXPECTED RESULT:
We expect H1 and H2 confirmed because:
1. Cancer signaling networks are highly non-random — hub proteins (EGFR, mTOR,
   AKT1) have much higher degree than peripheral nodes, creating real structural
   asymmetry that random rewiring should not reproduce in delta_r space.
2. The two-layer coupling (which nodes are connected in BOTH layers) is
   biologically constrained and unlikely to arise by chance.

If denied: the structural pharmacology framework would need to be reformulated
using metrics that account for degree-sequence effects.
